This article is a presidential proclamation declaring January 2014 as National Mentoring Month in the United States. The proclamation highlights the importance of mentors in guiding and inspiring young Americans to achieve their dreams. Mentors can be anyone, such as relatives, teachers, coaches, ministers, or neighbors. The article emphasizes that all children should have the opportunity to have a mentor. It states that young people with mentors tend to have better attendance in school, higher self-esteem, and a greater chance of pursuing higher education. The article also mentions various initiatives and programs aimed at promoting mentoring, such as expanding national service, promoting responsible fatherhood, and the First Lady's mentoring initiative. The proclamation calls upon public officials, business and community leaders, educators, and Americans across the country to observe National Mentoring Month with appropriate ceremonies, activities, and programs.